		<section id="blog-article">
			<div class="container">
				<div class="article">
					<p class="introduction">
						Navigating through sick notes, fit notes, doctors notes, med3s &ndash; whatever you call them &ndash; can get quite complicated especially if you&rsquo;ve been fortunate enough never to need them.  It can be difficult enough to jump through hoops to figure out if you need a sick note, why you need one or where to get one from at the best of times; let alone when you&rsquo;re feeling unwell.  Here&rsquo;s a handy guide we&rsquo;ve put together for reference.						
						<p>Q) Why do I need a sick note?<br />
Sick notes are generally used to show your employer that you are unwell and need time off work.&nbsp; They can also be used to advice your employer that you need a change in your working hours, work duties or adaptations made at work.&nbsp; Other organisations such as colleges and Universities may also ask for them, particularly if you perform poorly or miss an exam due to being unwell. </p>

<p>Q) How long do I need to be ill for before I can get a sick note?<br />
Your NHS GP is only able to provide a sick note if you have been sick for 7 days (5 working days) or more.&nbsp; If you have been ill for less than that, then you will be asked to fill in and complete a self certification/employee&rsquo;s statement of sickness form available here.</p>

<p>Q) What if my work insists on having a doctor&rsquo;s note instead of a self-certification form even if it&rsquo;s been less than 7 days?<br />
Some employers do insist on a doctor&rsquo;s note if you&rsquo;ve been sick for less than 7 days.&nbsp; For this, you will need a private sick note &ndash; something which MedicSpot can help you with.</p>

<p>Q) Does my employer have to abide by what is written on the sick note?<br />
No, the sick note provided by the doctor is classified as advice and your employer does not legally need to act on that advice.&nbsp; However, that said &ndash; it is very rare that your employer goes against the advice of the doctor.</p>

<p>Q) Do I need a doctor to provide me with a sick note?<br />
Yes, it needs to be signed by the doctor &ndash; normally a General Practitioner (GP.)&nbsp; If you have been in hospital, then you should ask the hospital doctors to provide you with one.</p>

<p>Q) Is a sick note, fit note, doctor note and a med3 the same thing?<br />
Yes, these are all the same thing.&nbsp; The term &ldquo;fit note&rdquo; replaced &ldquo;sick note&rdquo; in 2010.&nbsp; The main reason for this change was to try and get people to go back to work even if they can&rsquo;t completely resume their normal duties.&nbsp; Doctors often call these notes med3s, but their official title is a &lsquo;Statement of Fitness for Work.&rsquo;</p>

<p>Q) Can sick notes be backdated?<br />
Yes, doctors are legally allowed to backdate a sick note.&nbsp; </p>

<p>Q) How do I get a sick note?<br />
You can get in touch with your own NHS GP to get a sick note.&nbsp; However, if you need a private sick note if you&rsquo;ve been off work for less than 7 days or need a sick note at quick notice, then you can book an appointment with MedicSpot.&nbsp; Our online doctors can speak with you and email you a sick note the very same day.&nbsp; There is no additional charge for sick notes or more detailed letters.</p>					</p>
